  "explanation": [
    {
      "heading": "The Problem",
      "body": "Design a stack that supports `push`, `pop`, `top`, and `getMin()` — all in **O(1)**.\n\nNaive: iterate the stack to find minimum → **O(n)**. Unacceptable.",
      "appearsAtStep": 0
    },
    {
      "heading": "The Insight: Auxiliary Min Stack",
      "body": "Maintain a **second stack** that tracks the minimum at every level.\n\n**Push rule**: push to main stack AND push `min(new_val, current_min)` to min stack.\n\nNow `getMin()` is just `min_stack.peek()` — O(1).",
      "appearsAtStep": 1,
      "callout": "The min stack always has the correct minimum for the current stack size."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Why push current min on non-minimums?",
      "body": "When push(7) and current min is 3:\n- Min stack pushes **3 again** (not 7)\n\nThis preserves the invariant: **min_stack[i] = minimum of main_stack[0..i]**\n\nWhen you pop 7, you pop the corresponding 3 from min stack — and the minimum is still correct.",
      "appearsAtStep": 3
    },
    {
      "heading": "Pop — Keep Stacks in Sync",
      "body": "On `pop()`, always pop **both** stacks simultaneously.\n\nThe sync is critical: min_stack.size == main_stack.size at all times.\n\nWhen the actual minimum is popped, the next element in min_stack reveals the new minimum — no scanning needed.",
      "appearsAtStep": 6
    }
  ],

  "popups": [
    {
      "id": "pop-sync",
      "attachTo": "min-stack-viz",
      "text": "Same size as main stack — always in sync",
